subject: Fix errors in flavor unit tests
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2016-06-13 11:23:41.000000000', 'files': ['openstackclient/tests/compute/v2/test_flavor.py'], 'message': "Fix errors in flavor unit tests

This patch fixes the problems below:
1. flavor.unset_keys() is not checked in flavor unit tests.
   So check them in the tests.
2. test_flavor_unset_no_project makes no sense. It is OK to
   specify ``--project ''`` without raising any exception.
   It can pass because in the test, we set nither project
   nor property. So remove this test.

Change-Id: I04e537349936343b6d8c85b06bc6d0ba6bd41d6f
"}]
commit_message:
Fix errors in flavor unit tests

This patch fixes the problems below:
1. flavor.unset_keys() is not checked in flavor unit tests.
   So check them in the tests.
2. test_flavor_unset_no_project makes no sense. It is OK to
   specify ``--project ''`` without raising any exception.
   It can pass because in the test, we set nither project
   nor property. So remove this test.

Change-Id: I04e537349936343b6d8c85b06bc6d0ba6bd41d6f

commit_message:
Add 'links' to implied roles response

The API spec claims that a GET request for implied roles will provide a
link back to itself in the response[1]. This patch makes it actually do
that.

[1] http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/keystone-specs/api/v3/identity-api-v3.html#list-implied-roles-for-role

Closes-bug: #1564129

Change-Id: I43571cc8d759922a4d9107cadba590cf14d25b20

commit_message:
Add argument for efficient sparse image transfer

fetch_to_raw writes qcow2 image to volume by command 'qemu-img convert'.
When the large part of the image is sparse data, this is inefficient
because this command writes sparse data to volume without skipping it.

This patch adds the argument for skipping sparse data as below:
1. download qcow2 image from Glance (same as before)
2. extract it into raw format in local system by 'qemu-img convert'
3. write it to volume by 'dd xxx conv=sparse'

Change-Id: I9103da8e6d539e5b4ce7cc99336a7db9a5937051
Partial-Implements: blueprint efficient-sparse-image-xfer

commit_message:
Enhance FC multipath support

This patch enhances FC multipath by adding target_luns
to FibreChannelConnector.

Only target_luns is added because FCConnector has already treated
multiple wwn information in target_wwn.

target_luns differs among lun-masking tables (lun id tables)
in the following conditions.

1)
Storage/Driver manages lun-masking tables for each FC ports.

2)
The unused youngest number in the table is assigned to
the lun which is registered to each lun-masking table as lun id
because it makes the driver's implementation simple.

3)
User configures lun-masking manually for non-openstack purpose.
(I mean that when user configures lun-masking for some ports(not all)
the unused youngest number differs among lun-masking tables.)

And, to keep compatibility for the volume driver which does not
require such mechanism, if conn info does not include 'target_luns',
then target_luns is set to '[target_lun] * len(target_wwn)'.

Change-Id: If01d08b8d1fe434ec4eff1e22a68bcb9dc3e56be
Implements: blueprint fc-multipath-enhancement

[{'number': 3, 'created': '2016-05-13 02:33:01.000000000', 'files': ['neutron/objects/concurrency.py', 'neutron/tests/unit/objects/test_concurrency.py', 'neutron/db/concurrency.py', 'neutron/tests/unit/objects/test_objects.py'], 'message': "[DNM|TESTONLY] NeutronDbObject concurrency issues

Open for discussion [3].

This patch set displays some potential concurrency issues with the
current NeutronDbObject implementation. In it's current state, it is up
to the NeutronDbObject subclasses or their users to properly handle
concurrency.

Further patch sets will provide acquire_object/acquire_objects
contextmanager methods to the NeutronDbObject class. These methods are
to be used in place of get_object/get_objects whenever the user intends
to make changes to the object. These methods would start an
autonested_transaction.

There are (at least) two potential options for the implementation:

1. Based on the DB locks (e.g. SELECT FOR UPDATE/SqlAlchemy
   with_for_update).

   pros:
     - the object is guaranteed to not be changed while within the
       context

   cons:
     - prone to deadlocks ([1] and potentially when locking multiple
       objects)

2. Lock-free CAS based on object version counter. Can use SqlAlchemy
   version counter [2] or add our own. If conflicting changes are
   detected upon exiting the context (i.e. version counter held differs
   from the one in the DB), will raise OSLO RetryRequest exception.

   pros:
     - does not require locking

   cons:
     - require an additional field in the models

While opt.2 only prevents the conflicting changes, but does not
guarantee that the object does not change while within the context,
opt.1 may seem preferential. But even with opt.1 the user should not
expect that the changes made to the object while within the context will
get to the database as the autonested_transaction could fail on
flush/commit.

[1] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/OpenStack_and_SQLAlchemy#MySQLdb_.2B_eventlet_.3D_sad
[2] http://docs.sqlalchemy.org/en/rel_0_9/orm/versioning.html

[3] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2016-May/094862.html

Change-Id: I2b406fa70e5143e20fc96b32cf08aa61490bcf6a
"}]
commit_message:
[DNM|TESTONLY] NeutronDbObject concurrency issues

Open for discussion [3].

This patch set displays some potential concurrency issues with the
current NeutronDbObject implementation. In it's current state, it is up
to the NeutronDbObject subclasses or their users to properly handle
concurrency.

Further patch sets will provide acquire_object/acquire_objects
contextmanager methods to the NeutronDbObject class. These methods are
to be used in place of get_object/get_objects whenever the user intends
to make changes to the object. These methods would start an
autonested_transaction.

There are (at least) two potential options for the implementation:

1. Based on the DB locks (e.g. SELECT FOR UPDATE/SqlAlchemy
   with_for_update).

   pros:
     - the object is guaranteed to not be changed while within the
       context

   cons:
     - prone to deadlocks ([1] and potentially when locking multiple
       objects)

2. Lock-free CAS based on object version counter. Can use SqlAlchemy
   version counter [2] or add our own. If conflicting changes are
   detected upon exiting the context (i.e. version counter held differs
   from the one in the DB), will raise OSLO RetryRequest exception.

   pros:
     - does not require locking

   cons:
     - require an additional field in the models

While opt.2 only prevents the conflicting changes, but does not
guarantee that the object does not change while within the context,
opt.1 may seem preferential. But even with opt.1 the user should not
expect that the changes made to the object while within the context will
get to the database as the autonested_transaction could fail on
flush/commit.

[1] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/OpenStack_and_SQLAlchemy#MySQLdb_.2B_eventlet_.3D_sad
[2] http://docs.sqlalchemy.org/en/rel_0_9/orm/versioning.html

[3] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2016-May/094862.html

Change-Id: I2b406fa70e5143e20fc96b32cf08aa61490bcf6a

That module is included in auth_token/__init__.py, which in turn owns

This creates a circular import dependency.

commit_message:
Move auth token opts calculation into auth_token

The list of all auth token opts is currently calculated in opts.py.
That module is included in auth_token/__init__.py, which in turn owns
some opts that are needed by the former.

This creates a circular import dependency.

In order to fix such situation, this patch proposes to move the auth
token opts calculation into auth_token/__init__.py, so that it will
no longer need opts.py.

Co-Authored-By: Alfredo Moralejo <amoralej@redhat.com>

Closes-Bug: #1591913
Change-Id: If67d8bdb68a5ab9c07b960ad0111e2310ad82c83

commit_message:
Limit number of Keystone workers to 5 on master node

Currently number of Keystone workers is set based on number of CPU
threads. Each worker starts 5 connections to PostgreSQL, while we limit
number of possible connections to 100. This leads to situation where
Keystone fails to connect to the database, resulting in authentication
failure when Fuel command line client is used.

Change-Id: I94d5e995e78cdcb25d2ea3593701456526109ead
Closes-Bug: 1572498

Some FPB changes is required to make plugins v5.0 validation.

Now it is more easy to:
- to validate folders
- to perform nested validations
- to output arbitry messages
- to collect full report not stopping validation on errors

Code changes:
- Inspections and Checks is introduced.
  Checks is a bubbles of validator business logic that could be runned
  against abstract path or explicit file resource. They are easy to
  reuse and unit-test.
  Inspections runs set of Checks against given path. So now the
  validator itself is just declaration of inspections with setting
  and (almost) don't contain any logic.
- ReportNode inroduced.
  Reports is the unit of the validator output pipeline, they
  could be combined in report tree. Report tree being rendering
  forms the validator output. Checks and Validators are returning
  separate branches of this tree. Also ReportNode contain shortcuts
  for easy text messages creation and falure messages statistics.

Change-Id: Ib48534477dc854a7c608c2145564c71f05625c4b
Related-Bug: #1534126
Closes-Bug: #1539598
Implements: blueprint plugins-v5
"}]
commit_message:
Fuel plugin builder validator refactored

Some FPB changes is required to make plugins v5.0 validation.

Now it is more easy to:
- to validate folders
- to perform nested validations
- to output arbitry messages
- to collect full report not stopping validation on errors

Code changes:
- Inspections and Checks is introduced.
  Checks is a bubbles of validator business logic that could be runned
  against abstract path or explicit file resource. They are easy to
  reuse and unit-test.
  Inspections runs set of Checks against given path. So now the
  validator itself is just declaration of inspections with setting
  and (almost) don't contain any logic.
- ReportNode inroduced.
  Reports is the unit of the validator output pipeline, they
  could be combined in report tree. Report tree being rendering
  forms the validator output. Checks and Validators are returning
  separate branches of this tree. Also ReportNode contain shortcuts
  for easy text messages creation and falure messages statistics.

Change-Id: Ib48534477dc854a7c608c2145564c71f05625c4b
Related-Bug: #1534126
Closes-Bug: #1539598
Implements: blueprint plugins-v5

commit_message:
tempest: use host instead of hypervisor for aggregate test

For the type-1 hypervisors, the service hosts' hostname is different
from the hypervisor's hostname. But a recent commit changed to
use hypervisor's hostname for host to be added to aggregate in the
aggrate tests. This commit is trying to change back to use the
service host but will checking hypervisor's status, so that it can
continue to use service host's hostname but exclude those hosts which
are unavailable.

Change-Id: Ic7b6e99e190bb5f38a3dbaf57a4c690132344c32
Closes-Bug: #1591840

revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2016-06-10 16:59:39.000000000', 'files': ['doc/source/install.rst', 'devstack/plugin.sh', 'tox.ini'], 'message': 'Use ml2_conf.ini for OVN configuration options

The conversion from core plugin to ML2 mechanism driver
resulted in the OVN configuration options moving from
/etc/neutron/plugins/networking-ovn/networking-ovn.ini to
/etc/neutron/neutron.conf. The OVN configuration options
should have been moved to the ML2 configuration file
(/etc/neutron/plugins/ml2/ml2_conf.ini) like is done for
the ML2 OVS options.

In addition, "tox -e genconfig" was updated to generate

Change-Id: I4bcfc075a3805c8af4e845c89ba0fd81fb49474d
Closes-Bug: #1589205
'}]
commit_message:
Use ml2_conf.ini for OVN configuration options

The conversion from core plugin to ML2 mechanism driver
resulted in the OVN configuration options moving from
/etc/neutron/plugins/networking-ovn/networking-ovn.ini to
/etc/neutron/neutron.conf. The OVN configuration options
should have been moved to the ML2 configuration file
(/etc/neutron/plugins/ml2/ml2_conf.ini) like is done for
the ML2 OVS options.

In addition, "tox -e genconfig" was updated to generate
an ML2 configuration file with OVN configuration options.

Change-Id: I4bcfc075a3805c8af4e845c89ba0fd81fb49474d
Closes-Bug: #1589205

If we launch a instance in the case of unlimited project quota
and limited user quota, API would return internal error 500.
The code logic wouldn't check the case of unlimited project quota
in _calculate_overquota() and OverQuota exception was raised,

commit_message:
Fix booting fail when unlimited project quota

If we launch a instance in the case of unlimited project quota
and limited user quota, API would return internal error 500.
The code logic wouldn't check the case of unlimited project quota
in _calculate_overquota() and OverQuota exception was raised,
it cause infinite recursion in _check_num_instances_quota()

Change-Id: I7831266b6269ea5d9a3aaa32041158293a1d601e
Closes-Bug: #1491222

commit_message:
Update prechecks for Ansible 2.0.0

In Newton, kolla master works only with Ansible 2.0.0 and does not
work with Ansible 1.9.4, 1.9.5 and 2.1.0.

"kolla-ansible deploy" throws errors when Ansible version is
1.9.4, 1.9.5 or 2.1.0.  Ansible version 2.0.0 works fine.

Hence, updating prechecks to check if Ansbile version is 2.0.0.

Change-Id: I3b6563848866613b23309571fb80646e015b5cb8
Closes-Bug: #1586587

commit_message:
Rework Vertica plugin

Adding the metrics to monitor resource pools, resources
and projections per a node.

Metrics for Vertica are now:

vertica.connection_status
vertica.node_status
vertica.projection.ros_count
vertica.projection.tuple_mover_mergeouts
vertica.projection.tuple_mover_moveouts
vertica.projection.wos_used_bytes
vertica.resource.disk_space_rejections
vertica.resource.pool.memory_inuse_kb
vertica.resource.pool.memory_size_actual_kb
vertica.resource.pool.rejection_count
vertica.resource.pool.running_query_count
vertica.resource.request_queue_depth
vertica.resource.resource_rejections
vertica.resource.wos_used_bytes

Change-Id: I6e30d524ca77f900f231b9a626bfa853e31dbeb1

commit_message:
Accommodate savepoint errors caused during handling

A workaround for Py2K's shortcoming in not providing
for chained exceptions, replaces SQLAlchemy's "warning"
logic from https://bitbucket.org/zzzeek/sqlalchemy/commits/7a7483c0cf2f#Llib/sqlalchemy/util/langhelpers.pyT65
with one that explicitly chains oslo.db DBError instances together.

Work in progress!  Totally raw / only tested by a script
at https://gist.github.com/zzzeek/56802d6c3ae80ec18f8049b31d251d00

See also: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/326927/

Change-Id: I2e3bba85c73644bf0ff69cda9f83b5250e0f7fb7

commit_message:
tinyipa: Fix git clone tags when 1.6.5 <= git < 1.7.10

Add additional "git checkout" to tag to make sure
we are on the currect tag. This will
allow to support OSes with git >= v1.6.5 e.g. CentOS 6.7

Closes-bug: #1590912

commit_message:
Add type:deployment to release:cycle_with_miestones

Atleast in the case of the Kolla project, we follow the
releaase:cycle_with_milestones requirements, except that we sometimes
lag the final release by a week or more.  The reason is because other
projects are either late or make last minute changes in their
configuration which require a massive debug session on the part of
Kolla.  I can't speak for other deployment projects, but if requested
by the technicl committee I will find out which of them wishes to
make use of this extension to the scheduling.

FWIW I don't want Kolla to be release:independent - but that was at
the time of addition to big tent the only release cycle I thought we
could commit to without changes to the governance repository happening
now.

This addition was triggered by this review:
  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/297976/3

Change-Id: I056b2c1766cfcbbbc24859c1719605fb4ffdad43
Depends-On:  I4b342430f1d0db269d7b88d6b4226108fae4e370

commit_message:
Modify asserts for upgrades to include deployment

As is these tags may not be applied to deployment projects.  It
seems unsuitable to not inform operators that a deployment project
may support upgrades or rolling upgrades if they meet the
requirements just because the project isn't tagged as a
project:service.

Change-Id: I35e459b8e6c4f6f8c0dbd3fbb17f6104ca1717ee

commit_message:
Add fast8 to quickly test pep8 changes

This patch adds the 'fast8' test that Cinder has to os-brick.
It's a simple pep8 check against what has changed since HEAD.
This allows you to test for pep8 violations in files that you have
changed without testing the entire repo.

Change-Id: I4e3840d763d08a80c84ba00e2d5e5710a905ecf3

commit_message:
Move os-brick back to 1.3

After os-brick 1.4 was put into the gate we got a ~1/3 failure rate on
multinode grenade jobs, which blocks a bunch of projects entirely, and
hints at something quite wrong.

commit_message:
Ensure the float value of api version could work

Now if we pass a float value of api version such as "v1.0" or
"v2.0", client will raise a DriverLoadFailure error. Because
that client can't match a sutiable API entry.

So we should ensure that that some value like "v1.0" could
work as "v1".

Change-Id: I9631a083fd96a535153b6029b95a1d3c8d9966a2
Closes-bug: #1572616

commit_message:
Deploy Monitoring on the undercloud with Puppet

This is a first attempt to add monitoring support in TripleO.
It will reside on the undercloud and won't be HA right now.

The services are optional and disabled by default.

It will deploy:
* Sensu Server and API services
* Uchiwa, which is the open-source Sensu dashboard
* Add keystone-api check so we can validate oschecks are installed &
  ready to be consummed.

New parameters:
- enable_monitoring
- undercloud_sensu_password

It's using 2 Puppet modules that are the references and official modules
to deploy Sensu & Uchiwa.

Change-Id: I4bb3ede7f46bc19ce213b274ee604953583b293f
(cherry picked from commit 5b10a84e954d9bb058ce1ca12fbc5bb3ecbd3f4b)

commit_message:
Use debug instead of warning for pipeline implement error

Now pipeline is heavily used in Zaqar for controller, but unfortunately
operators will see a lot of WARNING errors in Zaqar's log because
some of the controllers don't implement one of the methods. That should
be a development details and it's not necessary to expose as WARNING,
otherwise, operators will be scared.

Change-Id: I98c574dc240372627d9e760fc0253c6340a9463f
